The Möller–Trumbore intersection algorithm is the fastest known ray triangle intersection algorithm and is useful for raytracer implementation.

Pseudocode for Möller–Trumbore algorithm:

// Given a ray R and a triangle T, find intersection point I

// Get triangle vertices
V1 = T.v1
V2 = T.v2
V3 = T.v3

// Get ray origin and direction
O = R.origin
D = R.direction

// Compute vectors for triangle edges
E1 = V2 - V1
E2 = V3 - V1

// Compute triangle normal
P = D x E2
det = E1 • P

// If triangle and ray are parallel, return no intersection
if (det < epsilon) return false;

// Compute vector from ray origin to vertex1
T = O - V1

// Compute barycentric coordinates
U = (T • P) / det
V = (D • T2) / det

// Check if point is inside triangle
if (U < 0 || U > 1) return false;
if (V < 0 || U + V > 1) return false;

// Compute distance to intersection point
t = (E2 • T2) / det

// If intersection occurs behind ray origin, return no intersection
if (t < epsilon) return false;

// Return intersection point
I = O + t * D
return true;

